CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW

2.1 Martian Dust Environment

Global Dust Storms:
Martian Year 34 (2018) produced a planet-encircling dust storm, representing the first in-situ measurements with dedicated meteorological sensors since the Viking Landers. Analysis from MY24 through MY35 confirms global-scale dust events occurred in MY25, MY28, and MY34. Daily gridded maps of column dust optical depth (CDOD) are now available from MY24 through MY35, enabling statistical characterization of dust loading for thermal system design.

Diurnal Temperature Variation:
Martian surface temperatures exhibit extreme diurnal swings. At equatorial landing sites (e.g., Viking 1, Pathfinder), daytime highs reach approximately 240 K (−33 °C), while nighttime lows approach 189 K (−119 °F). The maximum diurnal near-surface atmospheric temperature range is approximately 60 °C, twice that on Earth. Nighttime temperatures are constrained by CO₂ frost formation near 148 K. These extremes impose severe requirements on any coolant system.

Perchlorate Formation and Corrosion:
Perchlorates (ClO₄⁻) on Mars are formed, in part, through plasma chemistry during dust events. Electrostatic discharge (ESD) during dust storms, dust devils, and grain saltation generates free radicals that react with Cl-bearing minerals to form perchlorates. The oxidation power of ESD electrons is three orders of magnitude higher than that of UVC photons. This mechanism has significant implications for any system employing electrostatic fields in the Martian environment.

2.2 Electrodynamic Dust Shield (EDS) Technology

The Electrodynamic Dust Shield uses electrostatic and dielectrophoretic forces to remove dust from opaque, transparent, rigid, and flexible surfaces, operating via a multi-layer coating of electrodes. It has been identified as one of the feasible dust mitigation technologies for future Mars missions, with designs capable of preventing electrostatic breakdown at low Martian atmospheric pressures.

Critical Gap — High-Temperature EDS TRL:
NASA's EDS for lunar applications is at TRL 5 for ambient temperature operation after >15 years of development. For high-temperature (550 K) operation on Mars, the technology is TRL 2–3. Furthermore, recent experimental studies have revealed that EDS performance degrades significantly under simulated Martian low-pressure conditions. In tests at 700 Pa (Mars-equivalent pressure), the dust removal rate (DRR) falls below 20%, compared to >90% at atmospheric pressure. Mechanisms include reduced particle charging efficiency, loss of gas buoyancy, enhanced electrostatic agglomeration, and insufficient ionization density despite lower corona discharge thresholds. This represents a critical gap requiring substantial research before flight qualification.

2.3 Dust Sintering and High-Temperature Regolith Chemistry

Vacuum sintering dynamics of Martian regolith simulants have been studied at temperatures between 1175°C and 1250°C (1448–1523 K) for ISRU construction applications. Liquid-phase sintering occurs via selective melting of plagioclase and pyroxene, while olivine and chromite maintain structural stability. Particle size significantly affects densification and strength, with fine particles (d50 ≈ 12.7 μm) enabling low-temperature sintering via transient liquid phase formation.

For the SH-CORS system, the key question is the sintering threshold relevant to radiator surfaces. This thesis identifies that sintering onset may occur at significantly lower temperatures (as low as 550–700 K) when considering:

· Pressure-dependent sintering kinetics (Martian surface pressure ≈ 600 Pa)
· Perchlorate-mediated low-temperature cementation
· Electrostatic field enhancement of particle adhesion and fusion

This remains an open research question requiring experimental validation.

2.4 Fission Surface Power Heritage

The Kilopower reactor (1–10 kWe) provides heritage for NaK-cooled, Stirling-converted fission systems. Kilopower's specific power is approximately 15 W/kg for the complete power system, including reactor, shielding, and power conversion. The FSP program is currently developing a 10 kWe engineering flight unit for lunar demonstration by 2030. Primary and intermediate coolant loops in the FSP baseline design use sodium-potassium (NaK) alloy, with the primary loop operating at temperatures exceeding 600°C. The selected piping alloy is AISI Type 316L stainless steel, not aluminum alloys, due to corrosion concerns.

2.5 Lyapunov Stability in Thermal Systems

Lyapunov stability theory has been successfully applied to nonlinear thermal processes, including superheated steam temperature control in thermal power plants, ice-clamping devices actuated by thermoelectric coolers, and HVAC systems with thermal load estimation. These approaches integrate Lyapunov's second method with homogeneous system theory to construct Lyapunov functions with interval numbers for robust controller design under parameter uncertainties. This thesis extends these methods to the coupled thermo-electrostatic dynamics of dust-degraded radiators.

2.6 Physics-Informed Neural Networks for Heat Transfer

PINNs have been successfully applied to 3D heat transfer analysis, accelerating predictions compared to finite element methods. Hypernetwork-based PINN architectures (HxPINN) have demonstrated real-time monitoring of industrial heat exchangers, achieving mean absolute errors below 5°C compared to physics-based simulations while accelerating inference by 35–40x. PINN frameworks have also been developed to simultaneously identify boundary heat flux and thermal conductivity from sparse temperature signals, incorporating physical laws to reduce data reliance. These advances support the feasibility of PINN-based emissivity estimation for SH-CORS.

